# React Router Actions & Fetchers

## One fetcher per mutation concern

A single route action often handles multiple intents. Use a **separate `useFetcher`**
for each concern so responses, errors, and loading states don't bleed into each other.

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — isolated feedback per concern
const syncFetcher = useFetcher<ActionData>();      // sync products
const productFetcher = useFetcher<ActionData>();   // add / remove products
const submit = useSubmit();                         // save supplier info

// ❌ WRONG — add-product "success" fires the save-supplier banner
const handleAddProduct = (id: string) => {
  submit(fd, { method: "post" });  // shares useActionData() with save
};
```

## Success banners — use object reference as effect dependency

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — re-fires on every submission even when value stays true
useEffect(() => {
  if (actionData?.success) {
    setSavedOk(true);
    const t = setTimeout(() => setSavedOk(false), 4000);
    return () => clearTimeout(t);
  }
}, [actionData]); // the object reference changes each submission

// ❌ WRONG — second save never re-triggers the banner
}, [actionData?.success]);
```

## Return distinct keys per intent

```ts
// ✅ CORRECT — each intent has its own response shape
if (intent === "add-product") return { productOk: true };
if (intent === "sync-products") return { syncResult: { synced, error } };
return { success: true }; // save supplier

// ❌ WRONG — every intent returns { success: true }, errors are invisible
return { success: true };
```

## Sync in-place — never navigate when staying on the page

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — stays on supplier detail page
syncFetcher.submit(fd, { method: "post" });
// action returns { syncResult: { synced, error } }

// ❌ WRONG — navigates away to /app/products
submit(fd, { method: "post", action: "/app/products/sync" });
```
